## Architectural Decisions

### Why Pub/Sub over Kafka?
Pub/Sub is fully managed, integrates natively with Dataflow, and replay is handled at GCS layer. Kafka would be chosen for message-level replay, strict ordering, or existing Kafka investment.

### Why fixed AND sliding windows?
Fixed windows answer "what is the price now?" (5-minute snapshot). Sliding windows answer "what is the typical price?" (1-hour rolling baseline). Both are needed for anomaly detection — you compare the 5-minute spike against the 1-hour mean.

### Why event time over processing time?
Event time ensures every price tick is assigned to the window when the price actually occurred, not when Dataflow received it. Processing time windowing would silently assign late messages to wrong windows.

### Why BigQuery Silver has duplicates?
BigQuery streaming inserts are append-only. Dataflow's accumulating mode fires a window result twice — once at watermark, again for late data. Deduplication happens in the Spark batch job using ROW_NUMBER().

### Why two layers (Silver + Gold)?
Silver is raw and immutable — append-only, full history, used for reprocessing. Gold is clean and analytical — deduplicated, dimensional, optimized for queries. Separation follows the principle that raw data should never be modified.

### Why SCD Type 2 for dim_flights?
Flight attributes change occasionally (airline codeshare changes, route modifications). SCD Type 2 preserves history so historical price facts always join to the correct flight attributes for their time period.

### Why Dataproc Serverless over a managed cluster?
The batch job runs once daily and completes in 2-3 minutes. Dataproc Serverless charges only for job execution time — no idle cluster cost. A managed cluster would charge even when the job isn't running.

